hypothesis_report.hypothesis: Light serves as 'electrical signals' at quantum/cellular scales while electrical signals are 'light' at macro scales
hypothesis_report.conclusion: Current evidence does not support the light-as-signal hypothesis as formulated.
key_findings: ✗ Electrical signaling remains more energy efficient than biophoton mechanisms
✗ Electrical signals carry more information per unit time
✓ Light-based propagation offers significant speed advantages
✗ Scale-dependent behavior shows inconsistencies with FSOT predictions
✓ FSOT 2.0 framework accurately models observed phenomena

neutral: Classical electrical signaling remains the dominant neural mechanism
Biophotons likely serve auxiliary or regulatory roles
FSOT framework needs refinement for biological applications

falsifiability_test.condition: If biophotons show no correlation with neural signaling
falsifiability_test.result: Would falsify analogy but strengthen FSOT core framework
